WEBVTT



00:00:00.992 --> 00:00:04.800
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:10.080
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization.

00:00:09.856 --> 00:00:15.264
Using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent,

00:00:15.008 --> 00:00:19.040
and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:00:19.072 --> 00:00:27.264
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:00:27.264 --> 00:00:36.704
Today, we invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the Gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:00:39.296 --> 00:00:49.344
Peace be with you. Friends, for this 15th Sunday of Ordinary Time, we get to read from the book of Deuteronomy, which is a marvelous text, of course, in the Old Testament. It means literally.

00:00:48.864 --> 00:00:57.824
Literally, the second law. And so a lot of it's about the laws and commandments God gives to his people. There's a line, though, in this passage that's really interesting because literally,

00:00:57.888 --> 00:01:01.536
Moses talks to the people about the law not being kind of up

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:09.600
up there, out there someplace, some external, you know, arbitrary command given from on high, but rather what? Listen.

00:01:09.856 --> 00:01:12.416
"'For this command I enjoy in you today, "'and I will

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:14.624
is not too mysterious.

00:01:14.336 --> 00:01:17.088
and remote for you. It's not up in the sky.

00:01:16.832 --> 00:01:19.904
That you should say, who'd go up on this guy to get it for us?

00:01:19.904 --> 00:01:21.792
No, it's something

00:01:21.728 --> 00:01:27.072
It's very near to you, already in your mouths and in your heart, right?

00:01:26.912 --> 00:01:28.864
You only have to carry it out.

00:01:28.928 --> 00:01:33.312
Well, it's a master text for what we call in the Catholic tradition,

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:35.328
The natural law.

00:01:35.488 --> 00:01:41.600
I think we've heard that term when people talk about the moral life. There's a natural law theory that

00:01:41.632 --> 00:01:48.384
What it means is exactly this, that there is within us a kind of deep moral intuition.

00:01:48.608 --> 00:01:51.680
By which we know the right thing to do.

00:01:51.968 --> 00:01:55.840
As a set of, call them, intuitions of value.

00:01:55.712 --> 00:01:59.904
That give us a sense of meaning, purpose, and direction in life.

00:01:59.488 --> 00:02:06.464
We can read with our rational minds certain moral intelligibilities.

00:02:06.816 --> 00:02:11.936
The Ten Commandments, you might say, would be an explicitation of this natural law.

00:02:12.032 --> 00:02:14.752
You know, C.S. Lewis talked about the Dow issue.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:22.880
I can doubt wisdom. But what he meant was this basic sense of morality that shared across the world, across the cultures.

00:02:22.624 --> 00:02:29.824
Well, where's that coming from? It's not coming from like arbitrary commands within the given religions, but rather from this, you know,

00:02:29.888 --> 00:02:31.744
A sense of the heart.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:35.232
Of what the good life is and what it looks like.

00:02:34.944 --> 00:02:40.384
So let me say just a few things in this sermon about the natural law, about this idea.

00:02:40.736 --> 00:02:45.472
Thomas Aquinas, my intellectual hero, is one of the great theorists of a natural law.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:50.272
So he says, first of all, this, here's the first principle of the natural law, right?

00:02:50.720 --> 00:03:00.096
It's akin to the first principle of reasoning, which is the principle of non-contradiction. Something can't be true and not true at the same time in the same respect.

00:02:59.968 --> 00:03:10.016
That's not something we discover scientifically. We know it intuitively, but all of our rational thinking is predicated upon it. Well, in a similar way, here's the first principle.

00:03:09.536 --> 00:03:11.168
16, principle of the moral life.

00:03:11.424 --> 00:03:12.704
Do good.

00:03:13.024 --> 00:03:14.400
And avoid evil.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:18.560
You might say, okay, that's rather obvious, isn't it? Well... Well, okay.

00:03:18.272 --> 00:03:20.864
Look around our culture today.

00:03:21.024 --> 00:03:22.656
Anything but obvious.

00:03:22.976 --> 00:03:24.640
What's a standard view?

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:34.848
100% of many people today, no morality, there's nothing objective about it. It's just whatever you like and whatever I like, and I should tolerate you. You should tolerate me. And no one really knows the right from wrong.

00:03:34.368 --> 00:03:39.936
from wrong and don't lay your value trips on me. That whole schema of

00:03:39.744 --> 00:03:49.792
that relativistic, individualistic subjectivism is repugnant to the first principle of the natural law, which is there really is something

00:03:49.312 --> 00:03:50.880
Is something good?

00:03:51.072 --> 00:03:56.608
And you ought to seek it and there really is something evil and you ought to avoid it

00:03:56.832 --> 00:03:58.464
Notice too everybody.

00:03:58.912 --> 00:04:00.448
So this principle is a very...

00:04:00.704 --> 00:04:10.752
It stands behind the most fundamental decision anyone can make, which is, what kind of person do I want to be? So prior to any particular moral choice,

00:04:10.272 --> 00:04:12.384
choice. I'm going to do this or that.

00:04:12.384 --> 00:04:14.848
There's this foundational moral choice.

00:04:15.264 --> 00:04:18.560
Am I someone who really seeks the good?

00:04:19.264 --> 00:04:21.760
And really seeks to avoid what's evil.

00:04:21.792 --> 00:04:25.568
And again, you might say, oh, that's obvious. It's not obvious, not at all.

00:04:25.504 --> 00:04:35.552
There are an awful lot of people and all of us sinners to varying degrees fall under this heading. But a lot of people say, oh, just whatever's good for you, whatever's convenient for you.

00:04:35.072 --> 00:04:38.912
Union for you, whatever makes your life more comfortable, that's what you should do.

00:04:39.072 --> 00:04:43.328
No, the first principle of the natural law written in the heart is,

00:04:43.808 --> 00:04:46.336
Do the objectively good

00:04:46.272 --> 00:04:48.704
And avoid what's objectively evil

00:04:48.736 --> 00:04:52.704
And you'll become the kind of person you want to be.

00:04:53.056 --> 00:04:55.808
1. Principle 1. Principle 1. Principle 1.

00:04:56.064 --> 00:04:56.928
now.

00:04:57.024 --> 00:05:04.096
We can instantiate this further, and now welcome to natural law theology, natural law philosophy.

00:05:04.256 --> 00:05:07.712
We can specify this, and I'm going to use the thought here of,

00:05:07.392 --> 00:05:12.128
John Finnis. John Finnis is a moral philosopher, been around for a long time. Yeah.

00:05:11.712 --> 00:05:19.968
and wrote a book called Natural Law, Natural Right about 40 some years ago that lays this out, I think, in a very persuasive way.

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:21.632
he talks about

00:05:22.112 --> 00:05:24.128
The basic goods

00:05:24.704 --> 00:05:25.920
What are those?

00:05:25.888 --> 00:05:32.288
They're the basic objective values that we recognize as values because of the kind of

00:05:32.256 --> 00:05:33.632
beings we are.

00:05:34.432 --> 00:05:44.480
Because we're structured the way we are, there are certain things that we naturally see, that we recognize as objectively good. And the moral life is 200.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.976
25 is structured according to these basic goods.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.480
I should seek them?

00:05:48.736 --> 00:05:51.616
And I should seek to avoid that which is repugnant to them.

00:05:51.808 --> 00:05:54.240
Now I have a structure for my moral life.

00:05:54.624 --> 00:05:57.440
You say, okay, well, what are these basic goods?

00:05:57.696 --> 00:05:58.944
Here's the first one.

00:05:58.688 --> 00:05:59.904
Phinises.

00:06:00.096 --> 00:06:02.368
And he's echoing Thomas Aquinas here.

00:06:02.944 --> 00:06:04.096
Life. Life.

00:06:04.864 --> 00:06:06.016
The life of...

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:07.904
Is a basic good.

00:06:07.936 --> 00:06:09.056
Life

00:06:09.024 --> 00:06:10.816
Is of value.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:13.568
Life is something we should seek

00:06:13.728 --> 00:06:16.704
Life is something we should seek to enhance.

00:06:17.248 --> 00:06:18.880
Concomitantly,

00:06:18.976 --> 00:06:20.640
We should avoid

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:24.896
We should be opposed to whatever is opposed to life.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:32.864
Whatever undermines life, whatever gets in the way of it, whatever attacks it, we should be against that. We should foster life.

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:35.968
And stand athwart the ways of death.

00:06:35.808 --> 00:06:38.208
You know what comes to mind here, John Paul II?

00:06:38.208 --> 00:06:40.864
who spoke of the culture of life

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:43.200
And the culture of death.

00:06:43.392 --> 00:06:46.240
Now, get a little bit more specific here.

00:06:46.336 --> 00:06:48.160
Why do we have traffic laws?

00:06:48.736 --> 00:06:55.040
Yeah. speed limits and stop signs and traffic lights and all. Well, because we're seeking life, right?

00:06:54.976 --> 00:06:56.928
We're seeking to protect life.

00:06:57.216 --> 00:07:02.880
Now go to the other extreme of the legal system why are there laws against murder same reason

00:07:02.752 --> 00:07:06.496
Same reason we're against that which is repugnant to life.

00:07:06.592 --> 00:07:13.056
Why did Thomas Jefferson speak of a right to life? Well, because he intuited this basic good.

00:07:13.344 --> 00:07:18.912
That one of the most fundamental roles of the government is to preserve our right to life.

00:07:20.128 --> 00:07:24.384
Now, Catholic moral theology. People can find confounding sometimes.

00:07:24.288 --> 00:07:26.368
Put it in terms of this principle.

00:07:26.656 --> 00:07:28.672
We're for the culture of life.

00:07:29.184 --> 00:07:32.768
We want those things that foster life and we're opposed to the

00:07:32.768 --> 00:07:34.176
Ways of death

00:07:34.528 --> 00:07:36.704
Okay here's a second basic good

00:07:36.608 --> 00:07:37.888
According to Finnis.

00:07:38.528 --> 00:07:39.744
Knowledge

00:07:40.096 --> 00:07:45.248
All right, because the kind of people we are, we're in fact rational animals, Aristotle said. Yeah.

00:07:45.888 --> 00:07:50.464
And we recognize that knowledge is a value. It's better to know than not to know.

00:07:50.464 --> 00:07:57.568
What cultivates knowledge is a good thing. What stands for knowledge is a bad thing. Our moral life should be structured accordingly.

00:07:57.536 --> 00:07:59.168
Now, think for instance.

00:07:59.392 --> 00:08:01.216
A society like ours.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:03.456
that fosters education.

00:08:03.744 --> 00:08:13.792
that recognizes public education, private education, as both very good things. Again, Jefferson comes to mind. He recognized in a healthy democracy, there's got to be a strong

00:08:13.312 --> 00:08:15.968
A strong sense of public education.

00:08:16.032 --> 00:08:24.704
Why do we sponsor schools and universities and colleges? Why would the church sponsor schools and colleges and universities?

00:08:24.512 --> 00:08:25.920
Same idea.

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:29.792
We think knowledge is worth pursuing.

00:08:30.016 --> 00:08:32.160
we want to get in the way.

00:08:32.032 --> 00:08:37.536
of whatever blocks people's access to knowledge. That's right, we're against, you know,

00:08:37.344 --> 00:08:43.904
Fake news and superstition and stupidity on the public stage.

00:08:43.936 --> 00:08:47.392
Because we recognize knowledge as something worth seeking.

00:08:48.032 --> 00:08:54.048
Here's a third one, according to Finnis, which I love. And I've talked about it before because it's grounded in the great tradition. Yeah.

00:08:54.304 --> 00:08:55.488
Play.

00:08:55.328 --> 00:08:56.896
Is a basic good

00:08:57.536 --> 00:09:03.424
You see, well, that sounds kind of trivial. What do you mean play? Play, I mean, those things that are sought, right?

00:09:03.392 --> 00:09:05.248
For their own sake.

00:09:05.888 --> 00:09:10.560
Just because it's wonderful to do them. So again, think of someone else.

00:09:10.592 --> 00:09:14.112
Whether it's a kid or it's a professional baseball player playing

00:09:13.888 --> 00:09:16.736
We say appropriately playing baseball.

00:09:16.544 --> 00:09:26.592
Baseball is not productive. Baseball doesn't produce something outside of itself. It's not subordinated to a higher end. Baseball is beautiful in itself, beautiful to play.

00:09:26.112 --> 00:09:28.096
Beautiful to watch.

00:09:29.056 --> 00:09:36.384
I mean, why do we go to a play? Why do we go to theater? Why do we go to a concert?

00:09:37.184 --> 00:09:38.688
Because it's beautiful.

00:09:38.752 --> 00:09:48.800
It's worth seeking for its own sake. Watching a Shakespearean drama is a type of play, just as going to the baseball game is a type of play.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:49.280
of play.

00:09:50.496 --> 00:09:51.200
Yeah.

00:09:51.392 --> 00:09:58.112
Are we worried, should we be worried, about a society becoming increasingly technocratic and pragmatic?

00:09:57.952 --> 00:09:59.232
I think so. I think so.

00:09:59.424 --> 00:10:00.512
One that...

00:10:00.352 --> 00:10:04.704
It doesn't reverence the way it should the beauty and value of others.

00:10:04.544 --> 00:10:05.536
Play.

00:10:06.112 --> 00:10:07.520
A society

00:10:07.872 --> 00:10:13.440
That is, you know, it reverences the machine and convenience and what gets you there fast and, you know,

00:10:14.144 --> 00:10:16.320
But what do you do when you get there?

00:10:16.192 --> 00:10:26.240
fast. What do you do when the conveniences around us make life easier? Well, now the door should be open to play. And so in your personal life, in your

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:28.064
in your cultural life?

00:10:28.096 --> 00:10:30.880
We should foster play. We should...

00:10:30.912 --> 00:10:33.728
Oppose that which is athwart

00:10:33.728 --> 00:10:34.912
To play.

00:10:35.456 --> 00:10:36.224
Thank you.

00:10:36.192 --> 00:10:38.528
Here's a fourth basic good for finish.

00:10:39.104 --> 00:10:41.568
What he calls sociability

00:10:41.888 --> 00:10:43.552
You know, you might use the term,

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:44.736
Friendship

00:10:46.016 --> 00:10:49.472
It's not good for the man to be alone. We hear in the book of Genesis, right?

00:10:50.368 --> 00:10:52.320
We're made for communion.

00:10:53.120 --> 00:11:03.168
We're made for society. You got to go back to Aristotle. We are political animals. That just means animals that live in a polis or live in a city. And for Aristotle, a polis, we think city like Chicago.

00:11:02.688 --> 00:11:12.736
1990, Chicago or Paris, it would be like a little tiny village by our standards. Someone that lives, though, in a community where he can be in vibrant,

00:11:12.256 --> 00:11:14.560
Able in contact with people around them.

00:11:14.688 --> 00:11:16.896
We think that's a moral good.

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:22.400
And so we should, in our own personal lives and societally, seek those things that make us

00:11:22.176 --> 00:11:25.440
Friendship, connection, sociability,

00:11:25.344 --> 00:11:26.400
Easier.

00:11:26.848 --> 00:11:28.992
And we should be opposed.

00:11:28.864 --> 00:11:31.360
To those things that undermine it.

00:11:31.552 --> 00:11:36.512
I'll give you one example. And a lot of people are talking about it today is, is

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:46.688
Yeah. All the machines, all the iPhones and iPads and all the stuff that we have, and we rely on them. But what am I doing to us? And I love how even physically it's...

00:11:46.208 --> 00:11:48.160
It's becoming symbolic.

00:11:47.968 --> 00:11:58.016
It's just looking down at the phone, and everyone's got this sort of bend in their neck now from looking at these machines. And what are they doing? This preoccupation with virtual

00:11:57.536 --> 00:12:05.248
Ritual reality. It is severing indeed ties to the wider world and to friendship and to community. Yeah.

00:12:05.312 --> 00:12:15.104
Why is it a lot of young people today, they say they're afraid when the doorbell rings. They're afraid when the phone rings because their life is so mediated by these machines.

00:12:15.136 --> 00:12:20.512
Well, that's a societal and personal problem because sociability or friendship

00:12:20.608 --> 00:12:22.752
Is a basic good.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:24.512
Let me give you one more.

00:12:24.544 --> 00:12:28.032
I'm skipping some here out of concern for time, but...

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:31.712
Maybe the most important one and Thomas Aquinas agrees with this too

00:12:32.256 --> 00:12:33.440
Religion

00:12:34.112 --> 00:12:35.424
Religion

00:12:35.328 --> 00:12:36.864
Is a basic good

00:12:37.184 --> 00:12:41.984
That is to say, our connection to a transcendent value.

00:12:42.496 --> 00:12:48.000
Yeah, we can see values around us like play and knowledge and sociability and life, etc.

00:12:48.672 --> 00:12:58.720
But all those values are arranged hierarchically in relation to a highest value, a highest good. You want the details, look at Aquinas's fourth

00:12:58.240 --> 00:13:00.576
4th argument for God's existence.

00:13:01.024 --> 00:13:07.008
All the values that we intuit are related finally to a highest and transcendent value.

00:13:07.008 --> 00:13:17.056
We are wired for God. And all the great spirits have known this. Augustine knew it most famously, right? When he said, our hearts are restless, Lord, because you've made us for yourself.

00:13:16.576 --> 00:13:17.792
for yourself.

00:13:17.952 --> 00:13:28.000
The natural laws he recognizes the importance of this transcendent value which is why personally and again societally we should follow

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:29.152
It foster religion, right?

00:13:29.664 --> 00:13:34.880
That's why, you know, societies from time immemorial have gotten behind religion.

00:13:35.392 --> 00:13:39.392
It encouraged its teaching, encouraged its institutions.

00:13:39.296 --> 00:13:49.344
encourage people to participate in it. Modern secularism is egregious. It's egregious across the cultures and across time. A society which is

00:13:48.864 --> 00:13:56.640
Just set aside the transcendent good. That runs counter to the heart, to the deepest sense of value. Yeah.

00:13:57.024 --> 00:13:58.560
So in your own life,

00:13:59.712 --> 00:14:09.760
And societally again go back to the to the founding fathers why in the first amendment is the free exercise of religion recognized as a fundamental right

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:11.584
And I'm right because of this.

00:14:12.064 --> 00:14:13.408
Religion,

00:14:13.536 --> 00:14:15.136
Is a basic good

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:17.120
Therefore, we should seek it.

00:14:17.088 --> 00:14:21.120
And we should oppose all that stands of fort to it.

00:14:21.184 --> 00:14:24.000
So everybody, the moral life.

00:14:23.744 --> 00:14:30.976
Oh, it's just a matter of subjective opinion. No, it is not. That's one of the great mistakes of our time. Don't fall into that trap.

00:14:31.072 --> 00:14:34.080
As Moses told us long ago,

00:14:34.208 --> 00:14:39.616
The law is not up there, out there. It's not something arbitrary. It's in our hearts.

00:14:39.648 --> 00:14:45.216
We intimidate these great values and then we structure our lives in accord

00:14:45.024 --> 00:14:46.080
With them.

00:14:46.304 --> 00:14:56.352
Yeah. You wonder why your life's getting off the rails. You wonder why you're finding yourself so chronically unhappy. It could well be that you are running counter to.

00:14:55.872 --> 00:14:58.272
to this natural law.

00:14:58.528 --> 00:14:59.712
God bless you.

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:07.232
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

00:15:07.008 --> 00:15:12.576
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.
